description:
Just say the word 'Salerno' to a British soldier - and watch his eyes.

You'll see a sudden pride in them ... for Salerno was the blood bath of the invasion of Italy, a bullet-torn beach-head that made every man who landed on it a hero.

Here is the glorious story.
name: Sky Drop

description:
What was so special about the one Jap Zero with the Samurai sword painted on its fuselage? Why did even the best British pilots steer clear of it?

Steve Powers, ace pilot, found the answer when he arrived in Burma - for in his Hurricane, Steve would tackle anything that flew. But even Steve's guts and skill were not enough. His plane was plucked from the Burmese skies and he was left to fight on - for his very life, in the death-ridden jungle.

But that was what Steve Powers could do best - fight!
name: Bale Out!

description:
Down through Burma swept the ravening, looting, killing horde of Japanese. While in the South, the Allies built up men and guns at frantic speed for the counter-attack. But vital days were needed, or the British would be swept into the sea for the second time.

Four men - only four - went North to win those vital days, with their blood, if need be. Four men who faced the Japs and grimly made up their minds - "They shall not pass!"
name: They Shall Not Pass

description: The sign of the scorpion was their badge, and soon the Germans learned why . . . for the men of the Long Range Desert Group would fight as long as they drew breath. Their raids were as fast as the sting of the scorpion, and twice as deadly!
name: Scourge of the Desert

description: A survivor… alone on a cold, dark sea…this was the best that any RAF pilot could hope for if he ran up against Von Stein of the Luftwaffe. The German flew a jet-black Focke-Wulf 190, and his emblem was the ace of spades, the card of death.They called young Jack Collins a coward until the day he and his Hurricane took off to meet the Black Ace in mortal combat...
name: Black Ace

description:
Had they survived the landing at the deadly river-mouth, mined and ambushed by the Japs, and fought their way through the horrors of the jungle, just to be picked off on this ridge by Jap planes?

Was this the finish - here, when below them lay the secret Jap airfield they'd come so many blood-stained miles to destroy?

Was it blazes!
name: Doom River
